00:04:02.370 --> 00:04:05.540
And it came out of -- it
grew out of my first book.

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:08.930
It was supposed to be chapter
six of <i>Swing the Sickle</i>,

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:12.820
and the editors thought that
this discussion of slave prices

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:15.930
and slave people's values
just didn't fit with the rest

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:17.230
of what was in the manuscript.

00:04:17.230 --> 00:04:19.720
And they said, "You know, that
would be a great separate study."

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:22.140
And when I had written
that particular chapter --

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:25.770 position:56%
so I've been working on this stuff a
little bit longer than the ten years

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:28.490
because this was part of that
first book project that I did --

00:04:28.490 --> 00:04:34.550 position:56%
I found evidence of enslaved values,
monetary values on their bodies.

00:04:34.550 --> 00:04:36.690
And I found that women were
priced higher during their

00:04:36.690 --> 00:04:38.490
child-bearing years.

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:42.170
And I wanted to know why I had not
seen that in historical literature,

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:47.050
why I had not seen that outside of
some conversations women were sort

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:50.040
of put as secondary but outside
the conversations that were

00:04:50.040 --> 00:04:52.750
in the slave price
literature as well.

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:55.370
And so I wanted to know if
this was a national trend.

00:04:55.370 --> 00:04:58.930
I wanted to know, you know, for
all these years between the ages

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:02.500
of let's say 15 to 30
were women priced higher?

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:04.570
And that's sort of what
started me off on this.

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:07.370
And I was basically
collecting a database

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:10.850
of enslaved people's values --
the name, their age, their sex,

00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:12.620
their prices, and so forth.

00:05:12.620 --> 00:05:15.000
And some of these values come
in the form of appraisals,

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:18.870
which are the annual appraisals
that were done every year to figure

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:21.840 position:56%
out the projections of how much they
would be over the course of a year

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:23.540
or over the course
of their lifetime.

00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:26.930
And some of them also came
in the form of market sales.

00:05:26.930 --> 00:05:30.020
And market sales represent the
highest value that a person has.

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:32.580
It's the price that they
command in the auction block.

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:35.390
So this one little
chapter that I had written

00:05:35.390 --> 00:05:38.100
for a different book
became its own study

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:40.200
when I started doing
the research and learned

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:44.260
that women were not priced higher
than men and that there was just

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:45.960
that group of plantations
that I was looking

00:05:45.960 --> 00:05:47.480
at were actually the anomaly.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:48.870
They were the outlier.

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:50.560
And that for across the board --

00:05:50.560 --> 00:05:53.140
and I'll show you a slide in a
few minutes of the numbers --

00:05:53.140 --> 00:05:56.430
men were priced higher than
women across the board.

00:05:56.430 --> 00:05:58.680
And so you'll see a
little bit of this.

00:05:58.680 --> 00:06:02.830
And I'll show you my
influences where some

00:06:02.830 --> 00:06:06.270
of you may know Stanley Engerman,
he's an economic historian,

00:06:06.270 --> 00:06:10.010
co-author of <i>Time on the
Cross</i> with Robert Fogel.

00:06:10.010 --> 00:06:13.890
He saw me give a talk at Duke when
I was doing the research for this,

00:06:13.890 --> 00:06:15.730
when I was still thinking
that women were priced higher.

00:06:15.730 --> 00:06:18.090
And he came up to me
afterwards and said, "You know,

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.140
I think I have something
that might be useful to you.

00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:22.600
Do you have time to
come to Rochester?"

00:06:22.600 --> 00:06:24.920
I said, "Sure, why not?"

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:28.360
And I went up there with a
graduate student and my family

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.320
and literally left
with eight boxes --

00:06:30.320 --> 00:06:34.130
or seven boxes of archival
data that they had collected

00:06:34.130 --> 00:06:35.430
from <i>Time on the Cross</i>.

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:38.930 position:56%
So this was, like, one of the most
generous academic donations somebody

00:06:38.930 --> 00:06:40.230
could ever had.

00:06:40.230 --> 00:06:44.500
And it totally catapulted my
study in terms of the number

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:47.370
of data points that I had.

00:06:47.370 --> 00:06:49.660
But one of the things that I've
wanted to do with this book was

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:55.330 position:56%
to not just make people dots on
graphs and lines on charts, positive

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:58.450
and negative signs, I wanted to
show their humanity and I wanted

00:06:58.450 --> 00:06:59.890
to focus on their humanity.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:02.870
And I wanted to find a way to
tell their story as a commodity

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:05.760
but as a commodity that's also
a person and a human being,

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:08.860
similar to what Walter
Johnson did in <i>Soul by Soul</i>.

00:07:08.860 --> 00:07:12.100 position:56%
And one of the ways I did this was
to center the voices of the enslaved

00:07:12.100 --> 00:07:14.830
and to allow them to
tell these stories

00:07:14.830 --> 00:07:19.780 position:56%
about how they understood themselves
as human beings and as products.

00:07:19.780 --> 00:07:22.250
And I'll talk a little bit
about that in a few minutes.

00:07:22.250 --> 00:07:24.890
So just the data, this is what a
lot of people are interested in.

00:07:24.890 --> 00:07:27.750
I only really have it at
