So I'll respond to that based
on the records that I covered.

00:38:11.220 --> 00:38:15.840
Because I was studying the medical
records, I was looking at doctors

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:18.120
and even students that were
training that were working

00:38:18.120 --> 00:38:20.530
on their medical degrees
in the 19th century.

00:38:20.530 --> 00:38:24.330
And one of the students wrote
in his journal that he was happy

00:38:24.330 --> 00:38:27.160
because it was time for the
dissections and there's a time

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:28.750
of the year where they
do the dissections

00:38:28.750 --> 00:38:30.050
in the winter and the spring.

00:38:30.050 --> 00:38:33.630 position:56%
And he said, "I was happy to do this
and we had our first negro cadaver."

00:38:33.630 --> 00:38:36.230
And he said, "And I was so
surprised when we cut it open

00:38:36.230 --> 00:38:38.530
that the inside looked the same."

00:38:38.530 --> 00:38:41.110
The inside looked the same as
the white cadavers, you know?

00:38:41.110 --> 00:38:43.690
So this is on the eve
of racial science.

00:38:43.690 --> 00:38:45.530
You know? A lot of what I'm writing

00:38:45.530 --> 00:38:49.070
about happens before the American
Medical Association was founded.

00:38:49.070 --> 00:38:52.930
So it's before the regulation,
it's before cremation,

00:38:52.930 --> 00:38:55.540
it's before formaldehyde and some

00:38:55.540 --> 00:38:58.280
of the preservation chemicals
that were being used.

00:38:58.280 --> 00:39:01.960
Some of these physicians that
were training the students,

00:39:01.960 --> 00:39:05.470
one of them had nightmares
about his body being tampered.

00:39:05.470 --> 00:39:08.680
And he was one of the first
cases of cremation in US history.

00:39:08.680 --> 00:39:11.110
So he made sure that
his body was cremated

00:39:11.110 --> 00:39:12.410
because he didn't want that.

00:39:12.410 --> 00:39:14.290
But then there's others, there
are a few physicians at Harvard

00:39:14.290 --> 00:39:17.820
who wanted their bodies and their
skeletons to be fully articulated

00:39:17.820 --> 00:39:20.660
and on display so students
could study them.

00:39:20.660 --> 00:39:26.430 position:56%
So it's a tough balance because this
is also advancing American medicine,

00:39:26.430 --> 00:39:27.730
you know?

00:39:27.730 --> 00:39:29.170
And there's that.

00:39:29.170 --> 00:39:30.910
But then there's also
the exploitive part of it

00:39:30.910 --> 00:39:32.450
that we can't really ignore.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:34.000
So those are some of the things.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.180
They also measured Morton --

00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:40.210
Samuel Morton was part of a larger
trade in skulls in particular.

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:43.300
And Favin [assumed spelling] wrote
about this in The Skull Trade.

00:39:43.300 --> 00:39:47.200
And they would measure the brains
because they were trying to decide,

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:50.740 position:56%
like, were black brains smaller or
larger, what's the cranial capacity?

00:39:50.740 --> 00:39:53.550
So there was a lot of that and
there was conversation about that.

00:39:53.550 --> 00:39:56.570
But often I would find in these
records they would say whether the

00:39:56.570 --> 00:39:58.480
cadaver was negro or not.

00:39:58.480 --> 00:40:02.350
It would often say -- it would use
the word negro or negro skeleton.

00:40:02.350 --> 00:40:04.260 position:56%
There was one where they were
talking about a skeleton, they said,

00:40:04.260 --> 00:40:06.710
oh, this skeleton when
it was fully macerated,

00:40:06.710 --> 00:40:10.380
when they cleaned off all the
skin and the ligament and tendons,

00:40:10.380 --> 00:40:12.830
they got it all fully
articulated on the stand,

00:40:12.830 --> 00:40:14.610
they said the bones
washed up so white.

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:16.670
And this was a negro skeleton.

00:40:16.670 --> 00:40:19.300
And they said when he was
alive he stood six feet five.

00:40:19.300 --> 00:40:23.060
I remember when I saw that, that's
all I had on this particular case.

00:40:23.060 --> 00:40:26.840
But I was thinking did they know
that because they measured him

00:40:26.840 --> 00:40:28.760
when he was laying down or is
this something they actually knew?

00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:30.060
Like, I have no idea.

00:40:30.060 --> 00:40:32.510
But I was, like, they talked
about how stood six foot five,

00:40:32.510 --> 00:40:34.720
was it just because it
was the height or not?

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:37.650
And they talked about how they were
surprised that the bones could wash

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:40.740
up that white coming
from a negro cadaver.

00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:42.700
So those are the only
examples that I can think

00:40:42.700 --> 00:40:45.710
of off the top of my head.

00:40:45.710 --> 00:40:47.010
Other questions?

00:40:47.010 --> 00:40:52.050
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much, Dr. Berry
for this riveting lecture.

00:40:52.050 --> 00:40:55.500
I also am intrigued and disturbed

00:40:55.500 --> 00:40:57.410
by your discussion
of the cadaver trade.

00:40:57.410 --> 00:41:01.800
And I'm curious whether either
the resurrection men or the kin

00:41:01.800 --> 00:41:05.850
of the dead commented at all,
given your earlier discussion

00:41:05.850 --> 00:41:12.680 position:56%
about soul value and the stress that
the enslaved and freed black men

00:41:12.680 --> 00:41:16.740
and women placed on the
immortality of the soul regardless

00:41:16.740 --> 00:41:19.410
of what happened to the body,
whether the resurrection men

00:41:19.410 --> 00:41:25.490
or the kin of the dead commented
on perhaps the immateriality

00:41:25.490 --> 00:41:28.170
in some sense of what
was done to the cadavers,

00:41:28.170 --> 00:41:30.310
given the life of the souls.

00:41:30.310 --> 00:41:31.610
&gt;&gt; Daina Ramey Berry: Right.

00:41:31.610 --> 00:41:32.910
Good question.

00:41:32.910 --> 00:41:34.900
So in terms of the actual -- like,
Chris Baker, Grandison Harris,

00:41:34.900 --> 00:41:38.280 position:56%
the actual resurrection men that I
write about, that's what I'm working

00:41:38.280 --> 00:41:43.050
on now, is to try to find what they
-- you know, their own testimonies.

00:41:43.050 --> 00:41:47.050
I've just found them -- I
found them in records books,

00:41:47.050 --> 00:41:50.120
but I haven't found stuff
written and produced by them.

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:53.170
I found a few quotes
from newspaper articles.

00:41:53.170 --> 00:41:56.910
Like, one of the schools,
there was a school play.

00:41:56.910 --> 00:41:58.210
They did a Christmas ceremony.

00:41:58.210 --> 00:41:59.850
And they talked to Chris on stage.

00:41:59.850 --> 00:42:02.970
So I have some, like,
voice from him.

00:42:02.970 --> 00:42:06.320
They said that he was very
comfortable with bodies.

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:08.350
And I think that for him
-- and I don't know this;

00:42:08.350 --> 00:42:11.270
I'll hopefully learn this as
I'm working on the next book --

00:42:11.270 --> 00:42:13.560
that there's a separation.

00:42:13.560 --> 00:42:17.710
I'm hoping or I think that he might
believe that there's a separation

00:42:17.710 --> 00:42:22.240 position:56%
from the spirit, the soul leaves
the body when it departs this world.

00:42:22.240 --> 00:42:24.620
And I think there were some
people that believed that so

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:27.470
that they could stomach
this if they knew about it.

00:42:27.470 --> 00:42:29.870
I mean, there was one slave
narrative that I found

00:42:29.870 --> 00:42:33.390
by Charlie Grant who was
told to go exhume the body

00:42:33.390 --> 00:42:36.960
of a two-year-old infant and
bring it to his enslaver.

00:42:36.960 --> 00:42:40.970 position:56%
And his enslaver was then -- as
Charlie says, "He's going to send it

00:42:40.970 --> 00:42:44.080
to Virginia to a doctor and
they're going to cut it up."

00:42:44.080 --> 00:42:48.220
So there's an understanding from
some enslaved people, you know,

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:50.640
even in the 20th century
that are talking about that.

00:42:50.640 --> 00:42:53.100
There's also newspaper
advertisements of stories

00:42:53.100 --> 00:42:54.970
where they talk about
people being afraid

00:42:54.970 --> 00:42:56.730
to see Chris Baker on the street.

00:42:56.730 --> 00:42:58.320
You know, watch out,
he might snatch you.

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:02.170
So there was this sort of lore
among the free black community

00:43:02.170 --> 00:43:03.770
to watch out for him.

00:43:03.770 --> 00:43:07.340
But I don't have a sense yet of
what he felt or what he thought.

00:43:07.340 --> 00:43:11.930
I don't know about his spiritual
belief system, but people say

00:43:11.930 --> 00:43:13.580
that he and Grandison
Harris were really good.

00:43:13.580 --> 00:43:16.280
Like, there was a newspaper
article that talked about Harris

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:20.170
and he could break open
a casket and get the body

00:43:20.170 --> 00:43:21.650
out within a few minutes.

00:43:21.650 --> 00:43:23.860
And they just said he
was good at his craft.

00:43:23.860 --> 00:43:25.400
You know, it's kind
of a creepy craft,

00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:27.330
but they said he was
very good at what he did.

00:43:27.330 --> 00:43:30.050
And there were other body
snatchers that were Irish

00:43:30.050 --> 00:43:32.120
out in the Baltimore area.

00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:35.540
They were Irish, they were
not all African-American.

00:43:35.540 --> 00:43:39.170 position:56%
Sometimes -- and they worked as part
of a trading system where they had,

00:43:39.170 --> 00:43:43.050
like, middlemen just like we
see with the slave trades.

00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:45.290
And so it's a very elaborate system

00:43:45.290 --> 00:43:49.020
that we're still trying
to find out more about.

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:51.320
Thank you.

00:43:53.190 --> 00:43:55.240
&gt;&gt; Thank you for this talk.

00:43:55.240 --> 00:43:58.080
Your idea about a soul
value is really provocative.

00:43:58.080 --> 00:44:00.960
And I think it's something we'll
talk about as historians for,

00:44:00.960 --> 00:44:04.060
you know, the next
few decades to come.

00:44:04.060 --> 00:44:07.710
But it seems like having
an individual recognition

00:44:07.710 --> 00:44:11.750
of one's own soul value is a
resistive act in and of itself

00:44:11.750 --> 00:44:15.000
as your powerful example
with the suicide showed.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:18.600
And so I'm wondering how this
sort of played out day-to-day

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:22.600
and what were the consequences
of an individual recognizing his

00:44:22.600 --> 00:44:25.770
or her own soul value
or spiritual value?

00:44:25.770 --> 00:44:30.380
Because it seems like, you know,
if a slave holder notices this,

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:33.100
there are very real
tangible consequences.

00:44:33.100 --> 00:44:35.300
What measures did enslaved
people have to take

00:44:35.300 --> 00:44:37.240
to conceal this recognition?

00:44:37.240 --> 00:44:38.540
&gt;&gt; Daina Ramey Berry: Right.

00:44:38.540 --> 00:44:39.840
I think it's great.

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:41.710
I'm actually -- I've been working
on an article on soul value just

00:44:41.710 --> 00:44:43.850
to tease it out more than
what I do in the book,

00:44:43.850 --> 00:44:46.100
and I've been doing the
research for a couple months now.

00:44:46.100 --> 00:44:49.780
And just tracing, like, just
Frederick Douglass is one example.

00:44:49.780 --> 00:44:53.040
You're not going to see them
call soul value, you know,

00:44:53.040 --> 00:44:54.340
I'm not seeing that there.

00:44:54.340 --> 00:44:56.950
But he's talking about what I
would describe it, there was times

00:44:56.950 --> 00:44:59.890 position:56%
where he felt like he couldn't take
anymore and he was going to give up.

00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:03.520
And he describes this feeling
in the core of his soul.

00:45:03.520 --> 00:45:06.400
He says it's like a flame
that's going to go out.

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:07.700
It's almost done.

00:45:07.700 --> 00:45:10.730
He said than something came
over him and it rose again,

00:45:10.730 --> 00:45:12.400
he was able to stand up and move

00:45:12.400 --> 00:45:14.920
through that painful experience
whether it was a beating,

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:16.880
a whipping, a sale,
or what have you.

00:45:16.880 --> 00:45:20.230
And so I'm trying now to look at
how people went in and out of this.

00:45:20.230 --> 00:45:23.730 position:56%
Because I do think that some of
them struggled and some of them went

00:45:23.730 --> 00:45:25.190
through periods where
they were very low

00:45:25.190 --> 00:45:27.990
and they may not valued
themselves much.

00:45:27.990 --> 00:45:29.290
They may have felt like
they wanted to give up.

00:45:29.290 --> 00:45:31.800
And then there was something else
that kind of kept them going.

00:45:31.800 --> 00:45:33.890
And Douglass describes
it as a flame.

00:45:33.890 --> 00:45:37.480 position:56%
And I think that's a really great
analogy and a way to think about it.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:38.780
It's something that almost --

00:45:38.780 --> 00:45:41.770
for me it's got a dual purpose
because a flame burns, you know?

00:45:41.770 --> 00:45:45.100
So you think about the heat
and the power of that, of fire,

00:45:45.100 --> 00:45:46.510
and you also think of the fact

00:45:46.510 --> 00:45:49.960
that a wind can either take
it out or make it stronger.

00:45:49.960 --> 00:45:51.940
And so that's one place.

00:45:51.940 --> 00:45:56.020
So I think it also is expressed
through day-to-day resistance,

00:45:56.020 --> 00:45:59.430 position:56%
but then also having to measure when
to scale back so that your owner

00:45:59.430 --> 00:46:02.750 position:56%
or your enslaver doesn't see that
you have this will that's different.

00:46:02.750 --> 00:46:05.090
And I think a lot of enslavers
recognized enslaved people

00:46:05.090 --> 00:46:07.490
that had strong wills, and
they would try to do all kinds

00:46:07.490 --> 00:46:08.830
of things to combat that.

00:46:08.830 --> 00:46:12.840
So slavery is a system, I always
say, of negotiation, you know?

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:16.250
And sometimes literacy, writing
yourself a pass, you know,

00:46:16.250 --> 00:46:19.350
getting away, finding a way to
escape slavery might have been

00:46:19.350 --> 00:46:22.240
that one person's way of
expressing soul value.

00:46:22.240 --> 00:46:24.280
And I don't know that
I'm committed to saying

00:46:24.280 --> 00:46:27.160
that soul value is
all based on, like,

00:46:27.160 --> 00:46:30.250 position:56%
a Christian belief system, you know?

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:33.310
I think that there's some that
are African belief systems

00:46:33.310 --> 00:46:35.780
that would fall along this,
and it may even be people

00:46:35.780 --> 00:46:38.010
that don't believe in a
higher power, but they believe

00:46:38.010 --> 00:46:40.710
in something about
will and survival.

00:46:40.710 --> 00:46:42.950
And so I do see that, but that's
something that I'm sort of trying

00:46:42.950 --> 00:46:45.890
to tease out a little bit.

00:46:45.890 --> 00:46:52.260
I hope that answers your question.

00:46:52.260 --> 00:46:53.560
Okay, good.

00:46:53.560 --> 00:46:55.180
&gt;&gt; Thank you for your talk.

00:46:55.180 --> 00:46:56.480
This was amazing.

00:46:56.480 --> 00:47:03.070
And you kind of just touched on a
little bit what my question was,

00:47:03.070 --> 00:47:11.240
was this idea of soul or spiritual
value, did you see it more fleshed

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:15.000
out in the enslaved
who were Christian?

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:21.300
I mean, you talked about Isaac
met with his minister and how --

00:47:21.300 --> 00:47:23.540
you know, if they both
believed in the same god.

00:47:23.540 --> 00:47:27.020
So I'm just curious,
did that come up?

00:47:27.020 --> 00:47:28.320
How did that develop?

00:47:28.320 --> 00:47:31.620
And I liked the fact that
you mentioned that those

00:47:31.620 --> 00:47:35.820
who didn't believe in a higher
power still believed in themselves

00:47:35.820 --> 00:47:37.870
and also the culture they
came from, from Africa.

00:47:37.870 --> 00:47:39.600
&gt;&gt; Daina Ramey Berry: Yeah,
it's easier to see it with those

00:47:39.600 --> 00:47:44.210
that were Christian because they'll
talk about it because they believe

00:47:44.210 --> 00:47:46.030
that there's something
above them that governs,

00:47:46.030 --> 00:47:47.950
like a higher being, a god.

00:47:47.950 --> 00:47:52.110
But even people with African
religious belief systems believe

00:47:52.110 --> 00:47:55.990
in ancestor gods and other people
that have influence on their lives,

00:47:55.990 --> 00:48:00.720
even people that came before them
that they may have never met.

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:02.630 position:56%
And so there's that influence there.

00:48:02.630 --> 00:48:05.550
But I think for me, I saw a lot of
soul value in those that ran away

00:48:05.550 --> 00:48:09.440
and I always say to
people it doesn't mean

00:48:09.440 --> 00:48:12.620
that most enslaved people
escaped -- successfully escaped --

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:14.270
it just that the records
that survived

00:48:14.270 --> 00:48:17.120
because abolitionists wrote
them, wrote about these stories

00:48:17.120 --> 00:48:20.640
in newspapers or I've used William
Still's Underground Railroad

00:48:20.640 --> 00:48:23.190
and found evidence
of soul value there.

00:48:23.190 --> 00:48:27.220
Even in the published
narratives from 1825 all the way

00:48:27.220 --> 00:48:33.120 position:56%
through 1870's, the published
primary narratives, there's evidence

00:48:33.120 --> 00:48:34.480
of soul value woven all throughout.

00:48:34.480 --> 00:48:37.720
Some of them recognize
god as a Christian being

00:48:37.720 --> 00:48:40.550
and recognize their soul and
their spirit as something

00:48:40.550 --> 00:48:43.990
that lives beyond this here and
now in this space that they're in.

00:48:43.990 --> 00:48:48.320
And there's others that did
not necessarily say that

00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:52.830
or mention a Christian god but
still believed in something

00:48:52.830 --> 00:48:56.530
about themselves, that there's
got to be a better place.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:49:01.820
And for some, a better place
was Africa or parts of Africa.

00:49:01.820 --> 00:49:13.210 position:56%
For some a better place was to be on
the other side of the here and now,

00:49:13.210 --> 00:49:17.010
whatever that is for them.

00:49:17.010 --> 00:49:27.420
And so I'm sort of working through
how I want to describe that.

00:49:27.420 --> 00:49:35.050
But here I use evidence
of where they're talking

00:49:35.050 --> 00:49:40.190
about these pulls inside them to
know that they're not the commodity

00:49:40.190 --> 00:49:42.960
or that value, that dollar
value that's on their bodies,

00:49:42.960 --> 00:49:45.690 position:56%
to know that that's not who they are

00:49:45.690 --> 00:49:49.530
and that there's something
beyond that, that there's someone

00:49:49.530 --> 00:49:54.130
that encompasses much
more than that.

00:49:54.130 --> 00:49:55.430
Thank you.

00:49:55.430 --> 00:49:56.730
&gt;&gt; We have time for
one more question.

00:49:56.730 --> 00:49:58.030
&gt;&gt; Daina Ramey Berry: Okay.

00:49:58.030 --> 00:49:59.330
&gt;&gt; What wonderful talk, thank you.

00:49:59.330 --> 00:50:02.030 position:56%
One of the most complicated families

00:50:02.030 --> 00:50:08.610
in American history's is Thomas
Jefferson's, patron of this library

00:50:08.610 --> 00:50:11.350
and buildings named after him.

00:50:11.350 --> 00:50:14.140
And his slaves in many
cases are his children.

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:15.450
He's also a math guy and he
knows values of object --

00:50:15.450 --> 00:50:16.950
have you looked into his papers
and does he go into this?

00:50:16.950 --> 00:50:18.250
&gt;&gt; Daina Ramey Berry: Yes, I have.

00:50:18.250 --> 00:50:19.550
And actually, I want to read
you a quote that I use here.

00:50:19.550 --> 00:50:20.850
I looked at his work for
